,"links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6619"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13985"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86227"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"9091"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"13413"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13426"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37007"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44558"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103803","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/103803"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 26-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a six-month history of intermittent colicky abdominal pain. He reports that the pain has worsened over the past 24 hours, accompanied by nausea, vomiting, and abdominal distension. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 125/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.8\u00b0C. His abdomen is distended and tympanic to percussion, with diffuse tenderness but no guarding or rigidity. Bowel sounds are high-pitched and tinkling. A CT scan of the abdomen is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Diverticulitis","Volvulus","Intussusception","Mesenteric ischaemia","Appendicitis"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe CT image shows a characteristic \u0027target sign\u0027 in the left abdomen (Image), which is pathognomonic for \u003Cstrong\u003Eintussusception\u003C/strong\u003E. This appearance is created by the telescoping of one segment of bowel (intussusceptum) into an adjacent segment (intussuscipiens), resulting in concentric rings of bowel wall on cross-sectional imaging.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAppendicitis\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with right lower quadrant pain and tenderness, and CT findings would show an enlarged, inflamed appendix, often with surrounding inflammatory changes. These features are not present in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiverticulitis\u003C/strong\u003E usually affects the sigmoid colon and would show thickening of the colonic wall with adjacent inflammatory changes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVolvulus\u003C/strong\u003E involves twisting of a segment of bowel around its mesenteric axis. While it can cause large bowel obstruction, it typically presents with a \u0027whirl sign\u0027 on CT rather than the \u0027target sign\u0027 seen here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMesenteric ischaemia\u003C/strong\u003E would show findings such as bowel wall thickening, pneumatosis intestinalis, or filling defects in mesenteric vessels.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIntussusception in adults is relatively rare and often associated with a pathological lead point. Unlike in children, where intussusception is often idiopathic, adult intussusception frequently requires surgical intervention to address both the intussusception and the underlying cause. The chronic, intermittent nature of this patient\u0027s symptoms is typical of adult intussusception, which can have a more indolent course than the acute presentation often seen in paediatric cases. In this particular case the leading edge of the intussusception was an area of gastric heterotopia.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Intussusception in adults is often associated with a pathological lead point, such as gastric heterotopia or tumours.","The \u0027target sign\u0027 on CT is characteristic of intussusception, showing concentric rings of bowel wall.","Adult intussusception typically presents with chronic, intermittent abdominal pain and signs of bowel obstruction."],"references":["Marinis A, Yiallourou A, Samanides L, Dafnios N, Anastasopoulos G, Vassiliou I, Theodosopoulos T. Intussusception of the bowel in adults: a review. World J Gastroenterol. 2009 Jan 28;15(4):407-11. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2653360/","Tarchouli M, Ali A. Adult Intussusception: An uncommon condition and challenging management. Visceral Medicine. 2020;37(2). Available at: https://karger.com/vis/article/37/2/120/310449/Adult-Intussusception-An-Uncommon-Condition-and"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86227"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13985"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20879"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21916"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20879","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20879"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/vsvVOGSO9CV8dMgXju2nbj9rfGIslk.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/vsvVOGSO9CV8dMgXju2nbj9rfGIslk.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1500,"height":1125}},{"type":"media","id":"21916","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21916"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/uFneIsisGDBZqRVlp6PtpdvXXoZCHX.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/uFneIsisGDBZqRVlp6PtpdvXXoZCHX.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1500,"height":1061}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86227","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/86227"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-27T07:58:27+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-27T07:59:29+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6619"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103803"}}},"meta":{"c